sentence: What do Home Depot, Dollar General, and the US 10-year Treasury yield have in common?
Hint: They all act as though the US economy is exhausted, which puts more pressure on the passage and implementation of the Trump growth agenda, sooner than later.
At the bottom is a link to a comparison chart of Home Depot (HD), Dollar General (DG), and the 10-year yield.
In general, my mission is to show two different retailers versus each other and versus an economic gauge, the 10-year Treasury yield.
HD represents the most bullish retailer, whose clientele spans across multiple income levels, and who has benefited from the housing recovery.
Meanwhile, DG is considered a low-end retailer catering to the lower income spectrum, including many folks who have not participated in the so-called post-financial crisis recovery.
What pops out at me is the divergence between HD and DG, especially since the fall.
Whereas HD embraced and participated in the Trump rally, DG performed extremely poorly, and probably not merely because Amazon is eating everyone's lunch.
Which one of these pictures more accurately reflects the health of the consumer and of the US economy?
Or are there specific reasons why HD is so much stronger than DG, for DG to be so much weaker than HD?
Could it be that HD is expected to more directly benefit from the Trump growth agenda?

I don't know the answer, but the other thing that pops out at me is the directional similarity between the HD and the climb in 10 year Treasury yield â€” until the reaction to last week's FOMC meeting.

Putting aside the reasoning, let's just say that if the strong directional relationship in HD and the 10-year continues, and the 10-year has turned down after completing a July - March upleg from 1.32% to 2.64%, then HD could be at the start of a 20% correction (into the 120 area).
As for DG, it looks like it is in real trouble, and is on the verge of breaking down from a multi-month top formation.
What is that saying about the health of the consumer and the U.S. economy... and the direction of interest rates?
